      "writtenOn": "2026-07-23T14:32:56Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Thanks. The overflow is in the addition of two individually valid `uint32`\nrequest fields, not in either field by itself.\n\nThe added regression uses the existing 1,024-byte component fixture:\n\n- `offset \u003d 0xFFFFFF75` (`4294967157`)\n- `length \u003d 0x200` (`512`, within the negotiated transfer-size range)\n- mathematical end \u003d `0x100000175` (`4294967669`)\n- old 32-bit result \u003d `0x175` (`373`)\n\nThe old check therefore compared `373` with the padded component end `1056`\nand accepted the request. The component starts at package offset `139`, so the\nold `139 + 0xFFFFFF75` seek also wrapped to package byte zero. The unpatched\nmethod returned success and package-header bytes instead of rejecting the\nrequest.\n\nUnder DSP0267 v1.3.0 section 12.6, the length itself is valid but the requested\nrange is outside the component, so `DATA_OUT_OF_RANGE` (`0x82`) is the\nappropriate response. The patch does not widen either wire field. It widens\nonly the intermediate arithmetic so the range check evaluates the mathematical\nsum and returns `0x82`.\n\nI kept the comparison against `component size + baseline transfer size`\nbecause section 12.6 permits the final request to extend by that baseline\npadding. A blanket `UINT32_MAX` cap would be a different boundary and could\nreject that permitted padding for a maximum-sized component.\n\n`RejectWrappedOffsetBeforeComponent` covers this exact request. It passes with\nthe patch, and patchset 4 is Verified+1.\n",
      "parentUuid": "6e37c2cc_3770f3ea",
      "revId": "d5ab474d77d0bed1d17e3005d3e6cd12171dc462",
      "serverId": "adbd0a64-1f21-4d83-b585-671fe73cb6e4"
    },
